## Build a Single-File EXE (No Installer)


if /I "$(ConfigurationName)"=="Release" (
  call dotnet publish "$(ProjectPath)" -c Release -r win-x64 --self-contained true ^
    -p:PublishSingleFile=true -p:DebugType=None -p:DebugSymbols=false ^
    -o "$(ProjectDir)publish_signed"

  del /q "$(ProjectDir)publish_signed\*.pdb" 2>nul

  call "C:\Program Files (x86)\Windows Kits\10\bin\10.0.22621.0\x64\signtool.exe" sign ^
    /f "C:\path\cert.pfx" /fd SHA256 ^
    "$(ProjectDir)publish_signed\$(AssemblyName).exe"

  call "C:\Program Files (x86)\Windows Kits\10\bin\10.0.22621.0\x64\signtool.exe" verify /pa /v ^
    "$(ProjectDir)publish_signed\$(AssemblyName).exe"
)






> Recommended: run these commands in **CMD** or **PowerShell** (Windows).

### 1) Publish a single EXE (self-contained, win-x64)
```bat
cd C:\Users\ladan\source\repos\CableGlandPlanner_WinForms_DE\CableGlandPlanner

rmdir /s /q publish_signed 2>nul

dotnet publish .\CableGlandPlanner.csproj -c Release -r win-x64 --self-contained true ^
  -p:PublishSingleFile=true ^
  -p:DebugType=None ^
  -p:DebugSymbols=false ^
  -o publish_signed

dir publish_signed

2) Remove leftover debug symbols (optional)

del /q publish_signed\*.pdb 2>nul

Result you deliver to the user:
	•	publish_signed\CableGlandPlanner.exe  ✅ (single file)

⸻

Code Sign the Final EXE (Official Certificate / PFX)

1) Check SignTool is installed

where signtool

If not found, install Windows 10/11 SDK (Signing Tools).

2) Sign the EXE (PFX without password)

set PFX=C:\path\cert.pfx
set EXE=C:\Users\ladan\source\repos\CableGlandPlanner_WinForms_DE\CableGlandPlanner\publish_signed\CableGlandPlanner.exe

signtool sign /f "%PFX%" /fd SHA256 /tr http://timestamp.digicert.com /td SHA256 "%EXE%"

If SignTool still asks for a password (rare), try:

signtool sign /f "%PFX%" /p "" /fd SHA256 /tr http://timestamp.digicert.com /td SHA256 "%EXE%"

3) Verify the signature

signtool verify /pa /v "%EXE%"


